TY  - JOUR
AU  - Jansen, Mark
AU  - Winegar, Adam
T1  - Nonpecuniary Benefits: Evidence from the Location of Private Company Sales
PY  - 2025
Y1  - 2025/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/rcfs/cfae010
JO  - The Review of Corporate Finance Studies
JA  - Review of Corporate Finance Studies
VL  - 14
IS  - 3
SP  - 839
EP  - 879
SN  - 2046-9128
AB  - This paper investigates whether acquisition prices reflect a specific set of nonpecuniary benefits preferred by entrepreneurs: the quality of life (QOL) associated with the business location. Using data on private firm acquisitions, we find that target firms in high-QOL cities sell for a 14% to 20% premium. Traditional financial factors do not explain this premium, which dissipates when the buyer is unlikely to have preferences for high-QOL locations. Using wage-to-housing cost differentials to decompose local amenities and data on migration patterns, we find that QOL amenities have a greater impact on entrepreneurs’ location decisions relative to wage workers. (JEL G02, G32, G34, J32, L26, R39)
Y2  - 4/24/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rcfs/cfae010
ER  - 




