TY  - JOUR
AU  - Chu, Yongqiang
AU  - Diep-Nguyen, Ha
AU  - Wang, Jun
AU  - Wang, Wei
AU  - Wang, Wenyu
T1  - Shareholder-Creditor Conflict and the Resolution of Financial Distress
PY  - 2025
Y1  - 2025/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/rcfs/cfae005
JO  - The Review of Corporate Finance Studies
JA  - Review of Corporate Finance Studies
VL  - 14
IS  - 3
SP  - 804
EP  - 838
SN  - 2046-9128
AB  - Constructing a comprehensive data set of financially distressed firms that restructured their debts from 2000–2014, we find that firms with financial institutions’ loan-equity simultaneous holdings are more likely to restructure out of court than to file for bankruptcy. The effect is stronger when loans are oversecured and when the expected bankruptcy costs are larger. We use mergers of financial institutions and instrumental variable estimations to address potential endogeneity concerns. Firms with simultaneous holdings experience higher stock returns. The evidence suggests that mitigating shareholder-creditor conflict results in cost-effective resolutions of financial distress.
Y2  - 4/24/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rcfs/cfae005
ER  - 



